## Session 6: API Design & Pagination

### Feed API

**GET /api/v1/feed — Fetch news feed**
```
Request:
  GET /api/v1/feed?limit=20&cursor=post_id_abc123
  Authorization: Bearer {token}

Response 200:
  {
    "posts": [
      {
        "post_id": "uuid_123",
        "author": {
          "user_id": "456",
          "username": "johndoe",
          "display_name": "John Doe",
          "avatar_url": "https://cdn.example.com/avatars/456.jpg"
        },
        "content": "Hello world!",
        "media": [
          {
            "url": "https://cdn.example.com/media/img_789.jpg",
            "thumbnail_url": "https://cdn.example.com/media/img_789_thumb.jpg",
            "width": 1080,
            "height": 720
          }
        ],
        "like_count": 42,
        "comment_count": 7,
        "created_at": "2025-01-01T12:00:00Z",
        "viewer_liked": true,
        "score": 0.87
      }
    ],
    "next_cursor": "post_id_def456",
    "has_more": true,
    "feed_refresh_token": "token_xyz"
  }
```

### Post Creation API

**POST /api/v1/posts — Create post**
```
Request:
  POST /api/v1/posts
  Content-Type: multipart/form-data
  Authorization: Bearer {token}

  {
    "content": "My post text",
    "media_ids": ["media_abc", "media_def"],  // pre-uploaded media
    "visibility": "public"  // or "followers_only"
  }

Response 201 Created:
  {
    "post_id": "uuid_new",
    "created_at": "2025-01-01T12:00:00Z",
    "status": "published"
  }
```

### Pagination Strategy: Cursor-Based vs. Offset

**Offset pagination (page=1, page=2):**
- Simple to implement
- Problem: if new posts arrive between page 1 and page 2 requests, items shift — user sees duplicates or misses items
- Not suitable for real-time feeds

**Cursor-based pagination (recommended):**
- Cursor is the `post_id` of the last seen item
- Next page: "give me posts with score lower than the last post's score"
- Stable under insertions — new high-ranked posts don't affect pagination of earlier content

**Implementation:**
```python
def get_feed_page(user_id, cursor=None, limit=20):
    ranked_ids = redis.lrange(f"ranked_feed:{user_id}", 0, 199)
    if cursor:
        # Find cursor position in ranked list
        cursor_idx = ranked_ids.index(cursor) + 1
        ranked_ids = ranked_ids[cursor_idx:]
    page_ids = ranked_ids[:limit]
    next_cursor = ranked_ids[limit] if len(ranked_ids) > limit else None
    posts = batch_fetch_posts(page_ids)
    return posts, next_cursor
```

### Real-Time Feed Updates (WebSocket)

When user is actively viewing the feed, inject new posts at top without a full refresh:

```
Server → Client WebSocket message:
{
  "type": "new_post",
  "post": { ...full post object... },
  "position": "top"  // inject at top of feed
}

Client shows: "3 new posts — tap to load"
Client response on tap: inject posts at top of current list
```

**Rate limiting injection:** Max 1 real-time injection per 30 seconds to prevent feed thrashing for users following high-volume accounts.

### GET /api/v1/users/{user_id}/posts — User Timeline

```
Response 200:
  {
    "posts": [...],
    "next_cursor": "post_id_abc",
    "total_count": 1247
  }
```

This is different from the news feed — chronological, no ranking, only posts from one user.

### Interview Q&A

**Q: How do you implement infinite scroll on the client?**
A: Client requests first page (limit=20, no cursor). As user scrolls, when viewport reaches the last post, client fires GET /feed?cursor=last_post_id&limit=20. Repeat until `has_more: false`. On mobile, prefetch next page when user reaches 80% of current list.

**Q: Should `viewer_liked` be in the feed response or a separate API call?**
A: Embed it in the response to avoid N+1 API calls (20 separate "did I like this?" requests). Pre-compute by joining post_ids with the user's likes table in a batch query. Cost: one bulk Redis lookup per feed request.

